Argyll, Scotland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, (1st Feudal Lord of Lagg)":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Estate of Rock Hall, Collin, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Collin, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacGregor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McGregor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McGregor","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Griogair</b> or <b>Mac Greagair</b> ‘son of <i>Griogar</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name   Gregory  . Compare   Grierson  .","History: The Scottish Highland clan McGregor claims descent from the king of Picts and Scots Kenneth MacAlpin (Cináed mac Ailpín; 810–858  AD ). The origins of the clan are unclear. In the 13th century it was established on lands on the shores of Loch Awe and already in conflict with its neighbors of Clan Campbell. By the 16th century the McGregors had retreated deep into Glen Strae and acquired the nickname ‘Children of the Mist’. In 1603 the clan was abolished by royal edict and many members of the clan changed their surname. A year later, the chief of Clan McGregor and eleven of his followers were hanged in Edinburgh. Despite the proscription, the clan survived and supported the king in the Scottish Civil War (1644–51). The exploits of the Jacobite leader Rob Roy McGregor (1671–1734) were romanticized in a novel by Sir Walter Scott. The proscription was eventually repealed in 1774."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Malcolm MacGregor was born about 1297, in Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland, his father, Gregor MacGregor of Glenorchy, was 78 and his mother, Marian Gilchrist, was 59. He had at least 4 sons with Mary McAlpine of Finnick. He died in 1374, in Dumfriesshire, Scotland, at the age of 78."},"et":{"about 1297–1374":"umbes 1297–1374","1295–1374":"1295–1374","1297–1374":"1297–1374","1280–1363":"1280–1363","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1399–1457":"1399–1457","1420–1473":"1420–1473","1424–1473":"1424–1473","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1239–1300":"1239–1300","17 June 1363":"17. juuni 1363","1374":"1374","1220":"1220","1473":"1473","1363":"1363","1297":"1297","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1239":"1239","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1457":"1457","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1353":"1353","about 1297":"umbes 1297","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, (1st Feudal Lord of Lagg)":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Estate of Rock Hall, Collin, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Collin, Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1297–1374":"noin 1297–1374","1295–1374":"1295–1374","1297–1374":"1297–1374","1280–1363":"1280–1363","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1399–1457":"1399–1457","1420–1473":"1420–1473","1424–1473":"1424–1473","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1239–1300":"1239–1300","17 June 1363":"17. kesäkuuta 1363","1374":"1374","1220":"1220","1473":"1473","1363":"1363","1297":"12